  "reason_thou": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe LLVM `opt` tool crashes with a SIGABRT
signal due to an assertion failure in `llvm::BinaryOperator::Create`. The assertion
`S1->getType() == S2->getType()` fails, indicating an attempt to create a binary instruction
(like `and` or `or`) with two operands of different types. This happens within the
`instcombine` pass when processing the provided LLVM IR.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s
Log\n\nThe backtrace clearly points to the function `foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant` in
`InstCombineCompares.cpp` as the source of the problem. The sequence of calls
is:\n\n`visitICmpInst` -> `foldICmpInstWithConstant` -> `foldICmpBinOpWithConstant` ->
`foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant`\n\nThis flow indicates that `instcombine` is trying to
simplify an `icmp` instruction whose left-hand side is a binary operator and whose right-hand
side is a constant. The `opt` debug log confirms that the instruction being visited is `%cmp =
icmp ne <4 x i32> %or, zeroinitializer`. The crash occurs when `instcombine` tries to create a
new instruction to replace this `icmp`.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe specific
optimization pattern at fault is designed to transform expressions of the form `icmp eq/ne (or
(select cond, C1, C2), X), 0`. In our reproducer:\n\n-   `%cmp` is `icmp ne <4 x i32> %or,
zeroinitializer`.\n-   `%or` is `or <4 x i32> %sel, %x`.\n-   `%sel` is `select i1 %cond, <4 x
i32> splat (i32 1), <4 x i32> zeroinitializer`.\n\nThis matches the pattern where:\n-   `Cmp`
is `%cmp` (an `icmp ne` with a zero constant).\n-   `BO` is `%or`.\n-   The left operand of
`%or` is a `select` instruction (`%sel`).\n\nInside `foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant`, the
code at lines 3628-3636 attempts the following transformation:\n\n`(icmp ne (or (select cond,
NonZero, 0), Other), 0) -> (or cond, (icmp ne Other, 0))`\n\nIn our case:\n-   `cond` is the
scalar `i1 %cond`.\n-   `Other` is the vector `<4 x i32> %x`.\n\nThe transformation logic then
constructs:\n1.  A new comparison: `Value *Cmp = Builder.CreateICmp(ICMP_NE, Other, ...)`
which results in a `<4 x i1>` vector.\n2.  A new binary operator:
`BinaryOperator::Create(Instruction::Or, Cmp, Cond)`.\n\nThis is where the error occurs. The
`BinaryOperator::Create` call attempts to create an `or` instruction with operands `Cmp` (type
`<4 x i1>`) and `Cond` (type `i1`). LLVM IR does not allow binary logical operations between a
vector and a scalar of different types. The code incorrectly assumes that if the `select`
instruction produces a vector, its condition operand must also be a vector of the same
width.\n\nThe fix is to detect this type mismatch and make the types compatible. If the
`select` condition is a scalar and the other operands are vectors, the scalar condition must
be broadcast (splatted) into a vector of the same width as the other operands before creating
the final `or` instruction.\n\nTwo places in the function need this fix, as there are two
similar transformation patterns (the \"easy case\" and the \"harder case\").\n\n### 4.
Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nTo fix this, I will add checks in
`foldICmpBinOpEqualityWithConstant` to splat the scalar condition into a vector when
necessary.\n\n**Edit Point 1:** For the first transformation case.\n\n```cpp\n// File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp\n// Insert before line 3631:\n
if (auto *VecTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Other->getType()))\n          if
(!isa<VectorType>(Cond->getType()))\n            Cond =
Builder.CreateVectorSplat(VecTy->getElementCount(), Cond);\n```\n\n**Edit Point 2:** For the
second transformation case (the \"harder case\").\n\n```cpp\n// File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp\n// Insert before line 3654:\n
Value *NotCond = Builder.CreateNot(Cond);\n        if (auto *VecTy =
dyn_cast<VectorType>(Other->getType()))\n          if (!isa<VectorType>(NotCond->getType()))\n
NotCond = Builder.CreateVectorSplat(VecTy->getElementCount(), NotCond);\n```\n\n### 5.
Conclusion\n\nThe crash is due to a bug in an `instcombine` optimization that fails to handle
a type mismatch between a scalar `select` condition and vector operands. By adding logic to
splat the scalar condition into a vector, we ensure type compatibility for the newly created
binary instruction, thus fixing the crash and allowing the optimization to work correctly for
this vector code pattern.",
